● Honest take, having actually walked through the code:                                                      
                                                                                                                                    
  As a learning platform, your approach was pretty well chosen. You picked a problem that forced you to engage with each thing      
  seriously — you can't fake your way through Vulkan resource lifetimes, you can't fake spherical harmonics convergence, and you    
  can't fake Qt threading discipline. A "make a CRUD app to learn Qt" project would've taught you a tenth of this. The fact that the
   wavemanager has a CPU path because superposition needs neighboring waves and a compute shader doesn't fit the data dependency —  
  that's the kind of insight you only get by trying the obvious thing first and finding the wall.                                   

  What your approach actually got right (visible in the code):                                                                      
                                                                                                                                    
  - Vulkan abstraction is coherent. programVK.hpp:20-29 documents the call sequence as a contract, and the pipeline-library         
  decomposition (genVertexInputPipeLib, genPreRasterizationPipeLib, genFragmentShaderPipeLib) shows you understood VK 1.3's modular 
  model rather than copy-pasting a tutorial.                                                                                        
  - The dirty-flag protocol is real engineering. BitFlag in global.hpp plus eWaveFlags/eCloudFlags/eModeFlags is exactly the right  
  pattern for a render-loop-driven UI, and it's used consistently in both Manager and VKWindow.                                     
  - Threading is disciplined, not cargo-culted. std::execution::par_unseq shows up where the data shape supports it, and the comment
   in cloudmanager.cpp:338 ("62%-98% of total execution time") tells me you actually profiled. The QFutureWatcher + QMutex          
  modifyingModel pattern in vkwindow is the correct answer rather than the easy-but-wrong "raw thread + shared pointer" answer.
  - You can see growth across the tree. quaternion.* (older, manual float m[3], pointer-heavy ctors) vs. cloudmanager.* (lambdas,   
  ranges, std::optional, std::format) — the later code is visibly more modern. That's the learning landing.                         
   
  What I'd flag honestly, in priority order:                                                                                        
                                                            
  1. MainWindow is the load-bearing wart. 763 header lines, 2358 cpp lines, ~110 private members, 53 setup methods. This isn't a    
  Vulkan problem or a learning-curve problem — it's that you let one Qt class accumulate without splitting. A WaveDockUI and
  HarmonicsDockUI would more than halve it. If you do one refactor, it's this one — and the muscle you'd build is "notice when a    
  class is becoming a god class," which is the single most valuable Qt lesson you didn't get from this project.
  2. ProgramVK is also a god-class, but more defensibly. It mixes shader compilation, descriptor set management, pipeline assembly,
  and buffer lifecycle. The header contract papers over it nicely, but the cleanup() walking eight pointer collections              
  (programVK.cpp:58-138) is a smell. A std::vector<std::unique_ptr<ModelInfo>> would make the dtor trivial and the next refactor
  safer. Manual new/delete of long-lived owned objects is the one place modern C++ gives you a free win.                            
  3. extern bool isDebug/isMacOS/isProfiling/isTesting — works fine here, but it's the habit, not this instance, that matters. They
  couple every reader to a global, and once you've got four you'll add a fifth. A small RuntimeFlags struct passed down would scale 
  better.
  4. Config structs have no invariants. AtomixWaveConfig/AtomixCloudConfig are flat DTOs. The UI validates, but nothing downstream  
  does — so a malformed file or an off-by-one in a future signal handler silently produces a weird render. A validate() per struct  
  (or just std::expected<Config, Error> on load) is cheap insurance.
  5. Hardcoded Qt paths in src/CMakeLists.txt. Pragmatic for solo work, you flagged it yourself in CLAUDE.md, no real cost. Leave   
  it.                                                                                                                               
   
  The meta-take: the parts where Vulkan/threading/math forced you to think rigorously did teach you rigor, and it shows. The parts  
  where Qt let you keep adding to an existing class without complaining let you not learn that lesson, and that also shows. That
  asymmetry is the most interesting thing about this codebase as a learning artifact — it tells you what kinds of feedback loops you
   respond to. For the next ambitious project, picking a stack or a pattern that pushes back on monolithic accumulation (something
  with stricter module boundaries, or a habit of "split when a file hits 500 lines") would round out the gap.

  Solid work for "first time touching half this stuff." The Vulkan layer especially is better than a lot of production code I've    
  seen.
  